"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence from Captain R Williams and Captain S Airey, Air Safety Group and PACTS (HCS0006)&#xa0;Captain Williams is a former Chairman of the Air Safety Group (2006 – 2012), a wholly independent group of aviation professionals whose aim is to improve all aspects of aviation safety.  Captain Williams served as a professional Helicopter Pilot and spent \n17 years operating offshore in British Airways Helicopters between 1965 and 1983.  During that time he served at various times as the company’s Air Safety Officer, Flight Technical Officer, Training Captain, Flight Simulator Manager (for the world’s first \ncivil helicopter simulator, the S61N helicopter) and Base Manager \n(\nfor the company’s first oversees offshore operation\n in Germany)\n.   He then became a Senior Manager for ten years (1987 – 1997) in the \nSafety Regulation Group of the \nUK CAA as Head, Flight O\nperations (Policy and Regulations).\n&#xa0;\nCaptain Steve Airey \nread Aeronautical Engineering at \nManchester\n \nUniversity\n from 1981-1984. Joined the Royal Air Force and served as a helicopter pilot, including service in the Falkland Islands, the Gulf War, the Kurdis\nh Relief Operation and \nBosnia\n. Deputy Flight Commander, Detachment Flight Commander, \nAuthoriser\n, Squadron Air-Test Pilot, Day and NVG (Night) Formation Leader. Airline Captain since 1997, firstly on the BAC 1-11 and then on the Airbus A319/320/321 at Heath\nrow. Became a Fellow of the Royal Aeronautical Society in 2011.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\nAs mentioned this submission is aimed solel\ny at the first question posed.  This is simply because it has been some 30 years s\nince being intimately involved i\nn North Sea helicopter operations and it is not therefore possible to address those additional questions relating to how the UK’s \ncurrent \nsafe\nty compares to other countries, what steps need to be taken to improve current safety standards, how legislation could be improved and how effective the Regulators \nare \nin ensuring improvements are implemented.\n  In summary\n, based upon the available statisti\ncs in terms of known fatal accidents/fatalities \nover the 48 years of operations \nand \nthe \nestimated total number of flying hours an assessment can be made as follows: -\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;NORTH SEA HELICOPTER SAFETY&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n1\nst\n April 2009 - Bond Offshore - Eurocopte\nr AS332L2 – \nScotland\n – 16 fatalities\n23\nrd\n August 2013 - CHC Scotia – Eurocopter AS332L2 – Sumburgh – 4 fatalities\n&#xa0;\nThe 2009 accident was caused by a catastrophic failure of the main gearbox which, in turn, caused the main rotor to separate from the \nhelicopter.  The 2013 accident appears not to have been attributable to any mechanical malfunction and the helicopter was flown into the sea whilst on approach to Sumburgh airport.  The AAIB Bulletin on this accident appears to point to the possibility tha\nt the helicopter was allowed to enter a state of Vortex Ring, a low airspeed and almost vertical high rate of descent where the flow of air through the rotors re-circulates and the rate of descent increases and control is then lost.  Taking these two fatal\n accidents it would appear that the first was possibly due to a manufacturing and/or maintenance problem whilst the second may have been attributable\n to the\n pilots\n.  This is of course pure conjecture at this early stage in the investigation\n and the final A\nAIB report on the accident is now awaited.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;It has been difficult to estimate with any precision the total numbers of UK Operator’s hours flown \nin support\n,\n specifically\n,\n of the offshore industry over the whole period,\n as most UK\n operators have also been\n involved in other public transport operations.\n \n&#xa0;\nAppr\noximate \ntotal \nhours flown \n              \n1976 – \n2013 (38 years) \n              \n= 3,546,300 hours\nAt a\nn average annual tot\nal of \n              \n              \n              \n              \n              \n=      93,300 hours\n&#xa0;\nIt may be of interest to note that a\n brief \nsafety \ncomparison \nwas undertaken \nover a 3 year\n \nperiod \n(1979 – 1981\n – see below\n) between\n World Jet Transport operations \nand Offshore H\nelicopter operations\n.\n  This brief comparison sho\nwed that the offshore flying was \nrelatively \nsafer than the fixed wing worldwide public transport flying\n during that three year period\n.\n  It would perhaps be of further interest to do a similar comparison for the last five years\n \n(2009 – 2013) where the avera\nge \noffshore annual\n \nflying \nhours were approximately 74,265 hours. \nDuring this period there were\n 2 \nx \nfatal accidents and 20 \nx \nfatalities (\n1 x fatality per 18,566 hours and 1 x fatal accident every 2.5 years) and this shows a lowering of the offshore safety standards when compared to earlier comparisons. In the following comparison the annual offshore helicopter hours flown are more than double the average totals over the last five years.\n&#xa0;\nFIXED WING WORLD JET TRANSPORTYEAR   HOURS (,000)  FATALITIES   ACCIDENTS    FATAL ACCIDENTS&#xa0;\n1979\n              \n       13,906\n              \n              \n716\n              \n              \n        17\n              \n              \n    \n              \n14\n1980\n              \n       13,992\n              \n              \n812\n              \n              \n         22\n              \n              \n     \n              \n11\n1981\n              \n       13,904\n              \n              \n385\n              \n              \n         11\n              \n              \n       \n              \n  6\n1 Fatality every 21,850 hours for fixed wing&#xa0;NORTH SEA HELICOPTER OPERATIONSYEAR                    HOURS (,000)  FATALITIES              ACCIDENTS                  FATAL ACCIDENTS&#xa0;\n1979\n              \n              \n168\n              \n              \n \n1\n  